                    <h2>What Types Of Loans I Can Get As a Single Mother?</h2>
                    <p>A borrower with good credit can apply for any loan type with appealing terms and rates. But if you are a single mother and need emergency help, you must pay attention to many factors while choosing the best financial solution.</p>
                    <p>There are different loans for single mothers available. They may differ in the repayment period, loan amount, finance charges, and purposes. That is why you must consider all lending options and define the most beneficial one.</p>
                    <p>In all likelihood, a traditional lender will conduct a harsh eligibility check. That's why single parents should look for online loan companies or seek government grants. If you still don’t know what loan type will meet your expectations, keep reading. Below we will describe loans available for single mothers.</p>

                    <h3>Payday Loans</h3>
                    <p>A payday loan gives you an opportunity to borrow a small amount of money until your next paycheck. It typically requires high interest and must be paid back in no more than 30 days. Note that payday loans are not available in 16 US states, including New York, North Carolina, West Virginia, etc. That is why state laws are the first thing you should start with.</p>
                    <p>The greatest benefit of this loan type is that it is easy and fast to get. Payday lenders don’t have serious eligibility requirements. Even with a low income and credit, you can get approved.</p>
                    <p>If you are a single mother looking for financial help, consider payday as a last resort. Because of high interest rates and short repayment terms, it may be challenging to pay back on time. </p>

                    <h3>Personal Loans</h3>
                    <p>Personal loans for single moms provide flexible terms and amounts. It is a traditional loan type with relatively low interest and the ability to pay back in equal and regular installments. Personal loan is a great option for borrowers who need more than $1,500 to cover any financial issue.</p>
                    <p>Available amounts may vary from $1,000 to $5,000, and the APR is typically between 6.12% and 35.99%. To repay the borrowed sum you may have up to 60 months. Remember that even one missed monthly payment can spoil your credit and lead to debt. </p>
                    <p>If you are a single mother, it may not be easy to apply for a personal loan. But if you manage, it will be a great solution for you. As a borrower, you can get a secured or unsecured loan.</p>

                    <h4>Secured Loan</h4>
                    <p>A secured loan uses the borrowers’ property as collateral. And since lenders bear lower risk they charge less interest. Among the most popular types are mortgage, home equity and car title loans. These hardship loans are popular among borrowers with poor credit scores. You should keep in mind that if you fail to repay your debt, you can lose your property.</p>
                    <p>Secured loans require longer application procedures but help single mothers receive significant financial help with flexible terms.</p>

                    <h4>Unsecured Loans</h4>
                    <p>As you may guess, unsecured loans don’t ask for collateral. They are usually more popular among borrowers due to numerous reasons. Firstly, such loans can be attained within a few hours. If you need instant funds, it is for you.</p>
                    <p>Secondly, if you get an unsecured loan, you shouldn’t worry about your property. However, if you violate the deadlines you may be charged extra fees. At the same time, such lending options offer smaller loan amounts and shorter repayment periods. The APR may also be disappointing. That is why you should consider the unsecured loan pros and cons before making a final decision.</p>

                    <h3>Health Insurance</h3>
                    <p>Health insurance is a great way to feel more protected and prepared for medical emergencies. Thanks to this program, you can cover medical expenses arising from illness. If you have health insurance, you must make small but regular payments to the provider of services. As a single father or mother, you have different options for health plans. They may be founded by government or private companies. Among the most common solutions are:</p>

                    <ul>
                        <li>Medicaid</li>
                        <p>This governmental program offers affordable healthcare coverage to the representatives of some walks of life. Its services are low-cost or free for seniors, single fathers and mothers, people with disabilities, etc. The eligibility requirements are easy to meet, but you must have a stable monthly income to get approved.</p>
                        <li>A parent's health insurance</li>
                        <p>If you are under 26 years old, you can benefit from your parent's health insurance plan in most states. Even if you are married or have children, you are still eligible. </p>
                        <li>The Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP)</li>
                        <p>It is another way to take care of our nearest and dearest. CHIP covers the child's visits to doctors and other medical expenses. For this type of insurance, you can't be charged more than 5% of a family's annual income.</p>
                    </ul>

                    <h3>Scholarships for Single Mothers</h3>
                    <p>Young moms raising children on their own frequently dream of affording college tuition or getting a university degree. Luckily there are different student loan offers and education grants for people with low income.</p>
                    <p>For example, a Federal Pell Grant allows single dads and moms to access postsecondary education. Unlike loans, grants mustn’t be paid back, but you can’t receive them for more than 12 semesters.</p>
                    <p>All in all, if you are a single mom and want to get a higher education, you can qualify for special and general scholarships for women. Since student loans may be pricey, scholarships are more suitable for people living on childcare benefits. To manage it, you must monitor all available options and send your applications to grant providers.</p>

                    <h3>Auto Loans</h3>
                    <p>Thanks to an auto loan, a borrower may be able to buy a car without feeling financial pressure. You can apply for this option to purchase a new or used vehicle. Lenders like Wells Fargo allow you to get funds via online application.</p>
                    <p>Parents that bring up children on their own may not qualify for auto loans because of a credit pull and harsh income requirements. However, don’t think that it is impossible. If you have good credit and a regular source of income, you still have chances.</p>
                    <p>Auto loans usually have a long repayment period which may be up to 84 months. The APR typically varies from 5% to 14%. The available amount depends on your credit and the chosen lender but can’t exceed $100,000.</p>

                    <h3>Business Loans</h3>
                    <p>As you can understand from its name, business loans are used for setting up a company or small store. If you apply to traditional lenders, getting approved for such a loan will be difficult. You should be ready to go through harsh credit inquiries and deal with loads of documents.</p>
                    <p>However, you can consider two types of business loans with more favorable terms and rates. Since they are relatively easy to get and pay back, everyone should know about these options, especially people with financial difficulties. So, let’s take a closer look at them.</p>

                    <h4>SBA Loans</h4>
                    <p>Small Business Administration loans are beneficial for people who want to set up their businesses. It is a type of funding issued by a private lender but backed by the SBA. This loan type has strict qualification requirements, but if you manage to get approved, you will get many bonuses.</p>
                    <p>SBA loans typically come with lower rates. For example, traditional business options have an APR of up to 99%, while SBA-backed solutions charge 10%.</p>
                    <p>The repayment term is another pleasant surprise for people running businesses. If you opt for an SBA, you will have more time to repay the borrowed money. This period will depend on your business plan and vary from 10 to 25 years.</p>
                    <p>Moreover, SBA loans allow you to get larger loan amounts without collateral. Thanks to these loan programs, borrowers may be able to get up to $5 million.</p>
                    <p>However, if you are raising a child on your own and live on governmental benefits, self-employment with SBA will be very difficult to get. But if you are already running a small business and getting profit from it, you should try! SBA loans are the best alternative for people like you.</p>

                    <h4>Peer-to-Peer Loans</h4>
                    <p>Peer-to-Peer or P2P loans are social lending options with many advantages. This loan program allows people to get money from other people. How does it work?</p>
                    <p>P2P platforms connect people willing to lend money with the ones who need to borrow funds. Unlike traditional lenders, this option enables quick loan approval without setting income limits.</p>
                    <p>The decision as to your application approval is taken by the money issuer. Since the loan requirements are not stringent, a borrower can receive funds within one business day.</p>
                    <p>Apart from APR, most P2P lenders charge an origination fee of up to 8% of the loan. Sometimes borrowers may also face late penalties. That is why learning the loan terms and conditions is essential to avoid unpleasant surprises.</p>
                    <p>Peer-to-Peer loans are frequently used for business purposes and are suitable for parents raising children on their own. Such a lending solution allows people with bad credit and income to get financial assistance. If you can’t qualify for a traditional loan, P2P is worth trying. </p>

                    <h3>Home Loans</h3>
                    <p>Traditional home loans for single mothers may be challenging to get. Most lenders require borrowers to have good credit and a high monthly income. Luckily, you can apply for Down Payment Assistance Programs offered by different organizations and agencies.</p>
                    <p>FHA loans (Federal Housing Administration) with lower down payment requirements may become your helping hand. This mortgage loan is sponsored by the government and issued by a bank that is approved by the agency. Thanks to the FHA home loan program, you can get approved even with bad credit. </p>
                    <p>These loans come with the down payments of as little as 3.5%, which is entirely beneficial, especially for the first time home buyers. If you are a single parent, it is a great option for you because you may have up to 30 years to pay back borrowed money.</p>


